# R Coding Style

Write code that a human can read, scan, and edit in seconds. Prefer flat and
sequential over clever and nested. An LLM that writes simple code is more
useful than one that writes impressive code.

## Pipes and transformation

Use the magrittr pipe `%>%`. Break pipelines at logical checkpoints and assign
intermediate results to named variables. Aim for 3–5 steps per pipe block.

```r
# Good – two named, readable steps
data_clean = data_raw %>%
  filter(!is.na(value), year >= 2015) %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(date, label = TRUE))

data_summary = data_clean %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(total = sum(value), .groups = "drop")
```

```r
# Avoid – one giant chain that is hard to debug or modify
result = data_raw %>%
  filter(!is.na(value)) %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(date, label = TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(total = sum(value), .groups = "drop") %>%
  left_join(lookup, by = c("year", "month")) %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 20)
```

Break long chains at logical boundaries and assign intermediate results.

## Variable naming

- `snake_case` for everything
- Descriptive: `kfz_by_year` not `df2`, `accidents_clean` not `tmp`
- Path variables use the `p_` prefix: `p_data`, `p_output`, `p_geo`

## Assignment and operators

- Use `=` for assignment
- Use `%>%` (magrittr pipe, loaded with tidyverse)

## File paths

Always use `here()`. Never hardcode absolute paths.

```r
data_raw = read_csv(here("data", "kfz.csv"))
ggsave(here("output", "kfz_trend.png"), plot, width = 10, height = 6)
```

## Project structure

- `data/` — raw input files (never modify them in-place)
- `data/geo/` — geodata (shapefiles, GeoPackage, raster)
- `output/` — all generated outputs: charts, tables, exports
- `docs/` — Quarto documents and reports
- `R/` — R scripts

## ggplot2

One `+` per line, always:

```r
ggplot(data_summary, aes(x = year, y = total)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#CC0015") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_number(big.mark = ".")) +
  labs(title = "Title", x = NULL, y = "Total") +
  theme_minimal()
```

## Packages

Load everything at the top. Prefer `library(pkg)` over `pkg::fn()` for packages
that are already loaded. Exception: `lubridate::` functions are fine inline.

## Functions

Keep them short (≤ 20 lines is a good target). One function, one job.
Use `dplyr::case_when()` instead of nested `if/else`.
Use early `return()` to avoid deep nesting.

## What to avoid

- Nested function calls: `mutate(x = f(g(h(y))))`
- Magic numbers without context
- `attach()` or `with()`
- `for` loops when a `dplyr`/`purrr` approach is cleaner and equally readable
